 ---
 Critical Design Decision: Wikilink Resolution Strategy

 Obsidian resolves [[foo]] by finding any note named foo.md anywhere in the vault,
 with shortest-path-wins for ambiguity. OpenIdiom must handle this correctly.

 Resolution rules (Obsidian-compatible):
 1. Exact filename match (case-insensitive): [[foo]] → notes/foo.md
 2. If multiple matches: shortest relative path wins (same as Obsidian)
 3. If [[path/to/foo]]: treat as explicit relative path, match exactly
 4. If still ambiguous: log a warning, pick first alphabetically, store all candidates
 5. oi check --ambiguous-links reports all ambiguous resolutions

 Implementation: core/link_resolver.rs builds a title→path lookup table during
 indexing. The table maps lowercase titles to Vec<PathBuf> (multiple matches possible).
 Resolution logic runs after the full file walk, so all notes are known.

 ---
 Critical Design Decision: Parser Strategy

 Wikilinks ([[target]], [[target|alias]]) and tags (#tag, #tag/subtag) are NOT part
 of the CommonMark spec. pulldown-cmark will not parse them — it sees them as plain text.

 Parser pipeline:
 1. gray_matter: split file into frontmatter (YAML) + body content
 2. regex: extract wikilinks and tags from body content
 3. pulldown-cmark: extract headings (H1-H6) from body content
 4. Combine into ParsedNote struct

 This means pulldown-cmark is a targeted dependency — it earns its keep for
 robust heading extraction (handles edge cases like headings in code blocks,
 which naive regex would get wrong). Everything else is custom parsing.

