 Phase 5 — MCP Server Layer

 Goal: Expose vault operations as MCP tools so any AI assistant (Claude Desktop,
 VS Code Copilot, etc.) can query the knowledge base programmatically.

 NOTE: CLI-based AI tools (Claude Code, aider) can use `oi` commands directly
 via shell execution. The MCP layer is for tools that speak the MCP protocol.

 5.1 MCP server (mcp/server.rs)

 oi mcp serve                # start MCP server on stdio (default)
 oi mcp serve --port 3000    # start on TCP port

 Implements the MCP (Model Context Protocol) specification:
 - Transport: stdio (for subprocess integration) and optional TCP
 - Protocol: JSON-RPC 2.0

 5.2 Exposed tools (mcp/tools.rs)

 Tools exposed to AI assistants:
 - vault_status: get vault name, note count, index freshness
 - query_notes: structured query (same as oi query flags)
 - search_notes: keyword search (FTS5)
 - get_note: read a specific note's content and metadata
 - get_graph: get graph data (nodes + edges, optionally filtered)
 - check_vault: run vault health checks
 - ai_search: semantic search (if embeddings indexed)
 - ai_ask: RAG-powered question answering

 Resources exposed:
 - vault://notes — list of all notes with metadata
 - vault://tags — all tags with counts
 - vault://graph — full graph structure

 5.3 Design principles

 - Provider-agnostic: MCP is a protocol, not tied to any AI model
 - Read-only by default: AI tools can query but not modify notes
 - Future: opt-in write tools (create note, add link) behind a config flag
 - Authentication: none for stdio, optional token for TCP

