 Key Design Decisions

 1. SQLite over in-memory index — Persists between runs, enables incremental indexing, fast enough for 100k+ notes. No external database to manage.
 2. No custom vector DB — Cosine similarity in Rust over SQLite-stored vectors is fast enough for vaults up to ~50k chunks. HNSW can be added later if needed via the usearch crate.
 3. Pluggable AI from day one — The trait abstraction is minimal overhead and avoids a painful refactor later. Claude as default, OpenAI-compatible for flexibility, Ollama for local/private use.
 4. Embedding provider separate from completion provider — Users may want Claude for completions but OpenAI for embeddings (since Claude doesn't have a native embedding API). Config supports this.
 5. CLI binary name: oi — Short, fast to type, stands for OpenIdiom. Configured via [[bin]] in Cargo.toml.
 6. No watch mode in v1 — oi index is explicit. A --watch flag can be added later using notify crate. Keep it simple.
 7. Obsidian-compatible — Reads standard [[wikilinks]], #tags, and YAML frontmatter. Users can run OpenIdiom alongside Obsidian on the same vault. The .openidiom/ folder is self-contained.
 8. FTS5 before AI — Keyword search (free, fast, local) available before semantic search. Most queries don't need AI.
 9. Structured flags over DSL for v1 — Discoverable via --help, shell-completable, zero parser maintenance. Internal Filter enum supports OR/NOT for a future DSL parser — no debt.
 10. Byte-offset chunk storage — Embeddings table stores byte ranges + preview, not full chunk text. Full text loaded from disk on demand. Keeps DB lean.
 11. Cost transparency — All API-calling operations show estimated cost before execution. Usage metrics stored and queryable. Users always know what they're paying for.
 12. Streaming by default — LLM responses stream to terminal. Better UX for commands that may take 10+ seconds.
 13. MCP for AI tool integration — CLI-based AIs use oi directly. GUI-based AIs (Claude Desktop, etc.) connect via MCP server. Provider-agnostic by design.
 14. Parser strategy — gray_matter for frontmatter, regex for wikilinks/tags, pulldown-cmark only for heading extraction. Each tool used for what it's actually good at.
 15. Obsidian-compatible link resolution — Case-insensitive, shortest-path-wins for ambiguity, with warnings and a check command for unresolvable links.
